    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i was reading a manual for a cessna 172 and saw stuff about the pitot tube. can u explain how it actually works to measure airspeed? and why is it such a big deal if it gets blocked up?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The pitot tube on a Cessna 172 works by capturing the dynamic pressure of the air flowing into the aircraft, which is then combined with the static pressure to calculate airspeed. If the pitot tube gets blocked by ice, dirt, or bird droppings, the aircraft's instruments will display incorrect airspeeds, potentially leading to an unexpected stall or loss of control. This is why pilots are trained to regularly check and clear the pitot tube, especially in freezing conditions.",
      "source": "target",
