    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "i've heard pilots talk about weird \"ghost\" readings or instruments just acting up for no reason even when everything looks fine on the outside. is that actually a thing? like, could there be something tiny getting inside the lines that you wouldn't see during a normal walkaround?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Yes, that is absolutely a thing, and it is often caused by tiny, invisible intrusions like fine dust, sand, or even microscopic ice crystals that can enter the pitot tube or its connecting lines during a routine walkaround. These minute particles can cause a \"ghost\" reading or erratic instrument behavior because the differential pressure becomes unstable even though the tube looks clear to the naked eye. Sometimes, the issue isn't a physical blockage at all but rather a failing electrical component or a loose connection in the wiring harness, which can mimic sensor errors just as effectively. It is a classic example of how small, unseen problems can cause significant aviation safety issues.",
      "source": "target",
